}
```
___

You have a `formatDay` function, but then duplicate it inside `updateTime`. Instead you could call `formatDay` in both places, by just adapting `formatDay` a little:
```js
function formatDay(date) {
  let days = ["Sun", "Mon", "Tue", "Wed", "Thu", "Fri", "Sat"];
  return days[date.getDay()];
}

function updateTime(timestamp) {
  let time;
  ...
  let currentDay = formatDay(time)
  ...
  dateElement.innerHTML = `${currentDay}, ${hours}:${minutes}`;
}

...

function displayForecas(response) {
   ...
   <h5 class="card-title">${formatDay(new Date(forecastday.time * 1000))}</h5>
   ...
}
```

___

In relation to how the functions are organized, it's good that you're separating logic related stuff (like calling the API) from the HTML related stuff. But perhaps the names of the functions could reflect that a little better, like instead of `handleCitySearch`, it could be `displayCurrentTemp`, as it's basically just receiving some data and updating the HTML. Like that you could look at the names of functions like `displayCurrentTemp` and `displayForecast` and guess that they're both just displaying things.

Also other functions could be more clear, like `getCurrentTemp` instead of `handleCurrentTemp`, so you know it's speciffically _getting_ things.

